    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-30T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-30T12:00:00-05:00" n="1084"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1084">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760d.61/368: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-30T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 30, 1939—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 30—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>837. I have just been informed that the British broadcast from London at 7 p.m.,
                    Moscow time in reporting the expected departure tomorrow of the Finnish
                    delegation for Moscow stated that a Finnish newspaper this evening had published
                    a report alleging “when Paasikivi was in Moscow a high official of the American
                    Embassy handed him a personal message of sympathy from President Roosevelt
                    asking to be kept informed of the progress of the negotiations.” I need hardly
                    assure the Department that this report, assuming it to have been published in a
                    Finnish newspaper,<note n="61" xml:id="d1084fn61">The Minister in Finland had
                        informed the Department in his telegram No. 298, October 30, that the report
                        published in the Finnish press had been reprinted from the Stockholm
                        newspaper <hi rend="italic">Social-Demokraten</hi> (760d.61/367).</note> is
                    completely without <pb facs="0997" n="985" xml:id="pg_985"/> foundation. Neither
                    I nor any member of the Embassy staff saw Paasikivi during his visits to
                    Moscow.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Helsinki.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
